06791nam a22010215i 9780231543859DE-B159720220329044247.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220329t20182018nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018007540  a97802315438597 a10.7312/bagg181882doi  a(DE-B1597)514683  a(OCoLC)1057675625  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aB828.2b.P69 2018 4aB828.2b.P69 2018 7aREL0510002bisacsh04a14622300aPragmatism and Naturalism :bScientific and Social Inquiry After Representationalism /ced. by Matthew C. Bagger. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2018] 4c©2018  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. The Classical Pragmatists and Naturalism -- t1. Instinct and Inquiry -- t2. Religious Apologetic, Naturalism, and Inquiry in the Thought of William James -- t3. Deweyan Naturalism -- tPart II. Pragmatism and the Study of Religion -- t4. Pragmatism, Naturalism, and Genealogy in the Study of Religion -- t5. Language, Method, and Pragmatism in the Study of Religion -- tPart III. Pragmatism and Democracy -- t6. Reading Wayne Proudfoot’s Religious Experience -- t7. Public Reason and Dialectical Pragmatism -- tPart IV. Pragmatism and the Philosophy of Religion -- t8. The Fate of Radical Empiricism and the Future of Pragmatic Naturalism -- t9. Nonconceptualism and Religious Experience -- t10. The Oracle and the Inner Teacher -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost contemporary philosophers would call themselves naturalists, yet there is little consensus on what naturalism entails. Long signifying the notion that science should inform philosophy, debates over naturalism often hinge on how broadly or narrowly the terms nature and science are defined. The founding figures of American Pragmatism—C. S. Peirce (1839–1914), William James (1842–1910), and John Dewey (1859–1952)—developed a distinctive variety of naturalism by rejecting reductive materialism and instead emphasizing social practices. Owing to this philosophical lineage, pragmatism has made original and insightful contributions to the study of religion as well as to political theory.In Pragmatism and Naturalism, distinguished scholars examine pragmatism’s distinctive form of nonreductive naturalism and consider its merits for the study of religion, democratic theory, and as a general philosophical orientation. Nancy Frankenberry, Philip Kitcher, Wayne Proudfoot, Jeffrey Stout, and others evaluate the contribution pragmatism can make to a viable naturalism, explore what distinguishes pragmatic naturalism from other naturalisms on offer, and address the pertinence of pragmatic naturalism to methodological issues in the study of religion. In parts dedicated to historical pragmatists, pragmatism in the philosophy and the study of religion, and pragmatism and democracy, they display the enduring power and contemporary relevance of pragmatic naturalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aNaturalism. 0aPragmatism. 7aRELIGION / Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aBagger, Matthew C.1 aBagger, Matthew C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBagger, Matthew C., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, Scott.1 aFrankenberry, Nancy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrankenberry, Nancy.1 aGodlove, Terry F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGodlove, Terry.1 aKahn, Jonathon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKahn, Jonathon.1 aKitcher